## Doc & comment discipline

- **Default to no comments.** Write one only when the WHY is non-obvious: a hidden constraint, a subtle invariant, a workaround, behavior that would surprise a reader. If deleting it wouldn't confuse a future reader, don't write it.
- **Never provenance or narration.** No ticket/epic ids, no "added for/fixed by", no incident dates, no "formerly/used to", no comment blocks restating what the code does or walking through architecture — that story lives in the commit message.
- **Prune on touch.** Update or delete any comment your edit makes inaccurate; deleting bloat comments in code you are already editing is encouraged.
- **Protected comments — never delete:** lint/type suppressions (`eslint-disable*`, `@ts-ignore`/`@ts-expect-error`, `noqa`, `type: ignore`, `noinspection`), license/SPDX/copyright headers, and doc-comments on exported symbols consumed by doc tooling.
- **Docs prune, never append-only.** Doc edits consolidate and delete as readily as they add; CLAUDE.md gains a line only for a rule an agent would otherwise get wrong.

---

## Rules

- **Resume directives outrank phases.** If your turn opens with a parent directive, follow it and skip phases it supersedes.
- **One pass per file region.** Don't re-read a span you've already read in this turn.
- **One task only.** Implement exactly the task you were given; don't touch sibling tasks.
- **Test before commit, commit before done.** Phase 3 → 4 → 5. Two commits per task in history: source first (your `keeper commit-work` in Phase 4), state second (auto-committed inline by `planctl done` in Phase 5).
- **Budgets & trust** (standing rules — a resume directive skips phase text, so these hold even then):
  - **Two-full-suite-run cap per invocation, foreground only.** Run targeted tests first, then ONE full pass; never background a test run or idle-wait on one. The cap bounds full passes only — fix-then-targeted-rerun on your own code is uncapped.
  - **Never disable a test to get green** — no skip markers, commented assertions, weakened matchers, or deletions. Escalate instead.
  - **Mandatory delivery self-check on every path** (including no-op tasks) via `keeper session-state`; never reason over raw `git status` / porcelain.
  - **Trust git over envelopes.** On a suspect `keeper commit-work` / `planctl done` envelope, run `git log` ground truth, side with git, retry the verb once, then `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE` carrying both outputs.
  - **Return cap: 5 template lines + at most 3 note lines,** evidence by reference, no self-check narration.
- **`keeper commit-work` failures surface as `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE`,** except `lint_failed` — read the named files, fix per stderr, re-stage, re-invoke. Don't patch the tool you're calling.
- **No `TodoWrite`.** Planctl tracks tasks.
